<HEAD>Nina, Pinta, Santa Maria Back In Port After Storm</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HUELVA, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Christopher Columbus could have told them
it wouldn't be easy.
   Ninety Spaniards sailing in exact replicas of Columbus' three
ships, the Nina, Pinta and Santa Maria, departed from this
southwestern Atlantic port Friday on a six-month Mediterranean sea
trial.
   But by Saturday, the explorers, who are preparing for a planned
1992 re-creation of Columbus' voyage to the New World, found
themselves back in port after they were blown to land by a
windstorm.
   Undaunted, Spanish navy Capt. Santiago Bolivar, the leader of
the mission, told reporters Saturday: ``We're going to wait out the
winds before starting out again for our first destination.'' That
destination is Almeria, a southwestern Spanish port roughly 310
miles east of Huelva.
   The ships' joyful sendoff Friday coincided with the 498th
anniversary of the day Columbus began his first voyage to what
would become known as America.
   Spain, which bankrolled Columbus, spent $2 million to build the
three ships from Galician pine and oak from the Pyrenees.
   The ships were built to help promote the Expo '92 World's Fair
in the southern city of Seville and to commemorate the 500th
anniversary of Columbus' legendary voyage.
   Expo '92 is expected to attract 20 million visitors to Seville
from April to October 1992.
   While the sailors will attempt to follow the exact sailing
methods of Columbus and his intrepid men, the ships are equipped
with sophisticated equipment to navigate via satellite and carry
modern-day lighting.
</TEXT>
