<DESCRIPT>  HISTORY; FOUND; NORTH-AMERICA; FESTIVAL  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  IN FOURTEEN-HUNDRED and Ninety-two,;    Columbus sailed the ocean blue.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Travel  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  THE GREAT COLUMBUS CHASE
DESPITE DIARIES, MUCH ABOUT MAN REMAINS A
MYSTERY  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Cover Story
See also related stories on P. 1T, 7T, 8T, 9T and 10T of this section
The Great Columbus Chase  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     That much, we know, is true. Somebody named Christopher Columbus, or
Cristoforo Colombo (the Italian version) or Cristobal Colon (the Spanish
spelling), did sail from a tiny port in southern Spain on Aug. 3, 1492, cross
the Atlantic, land somewhere in the Bahamas, then return to spread the word
that a new world awaited those who embraced God, glory and gold.;    His
diaries exist. The logs of his journeys to the Americas exist. We know where
he died and have some idea where he might be buried. We also have some
indication that he was no saint or selfless explorer, as generations of
American school kids have been taught. Indeed, there is evidence to suggest he
was greedy, malicious, conniving and a cheat. (See accompanying article by
Nora Villagran.);    Whatever, Spain is getting very excited about 1992 and
the quincentennial of the Columbus voyage. Barcelona is holding the summer
Olympic Games and Seville is holding the 1992 Expo. Both events will be
heavily laced with Columbus celebrations. Italy is also gearing up for a fete
or two to honor its native son, especially in his home town of Genoa.;    But
the celebrations are not confined to Europe. From San Jose to Columbus, Ohio;
from Toronto to Miami, there are events planned all next year to honor the man
who officially (if not factually) discovered America, though he's several
parts enigma.;    His legacy is uncertain, his contributions unclear. But he
has left footprints all over Europe.;    Following those footprints adds
little to the truth about the man -- but the footprints do take you to some
interesting spots.;    Over the next several weeks, from Genoa to Barcelona,
from Granada to a tiny monastery in the pollution-clouded Rio Tinto valley,
we'll chase Columbus around his old haunts, 499 years after he stepped aboard
the Santa Maria and sailed off to immortality.;    One of the big mysteries
about Columbus has always been where he was born. The Italians insist he was
born in Genoa about 1451, the son of Domenico Colombo and Susanna
Fontanarossa. His father, so one version goes, was a wool merchant and weaver
who caught the eye of the doge of Genoa and was made gatekeeper of the
Olivella Gate.;    Another version has him being a Jew born in Spain; another,
that he was non-Jewish, born in Spain.;    Or, even, would you believe,
Norwegian? Tor Borch Sannes, a Norwegian researcher of maritime history, says
in a new book that Columbus was born in the small community of Hyen in
Nordsfjord in western Norway. He was named Christopher Bonde, a Norwegian name
meaning "farmer," but called himself Christopher Colon -- after "colonus," the
Latin word for farmer.;    The Bonde family, so this version goes, was
involved with the royal families of Sweden and Norway and left Norway for
Genoa in the 15th century because of conflicts between the two royal
families.;    The Scandinavians have always been miffed that Columbus gets all
the publicity for discovering the Western Hemisphere, citing fairly convincing
evidence that Viking sailors explored the New World around the year 1000,
almost 500 years before Columbus sailed. (Stephen Birnbaum discusses this
issue, Page 2T.);    Italian historian Gianni Granzotto, in a 1984 biography,
says Columbus began his sailing career as a boy, perhaps as young as 13,
accompanying wool shipments belonging to his father.;    Off to sea;    In
1476, according to American historian Samuel Eliot Morison, a Genoese convoy
Columbus was with was attacked by a Franco-Portuguese war fleet of about a
dozen vessels, and Columbus was wounded in the battle. He escaped his sinking
ship and managed to swim and cling to an oar until he reached the shore of
Portugal near Lagos.;    He apparently was not taken prisoner, because the
next year he sailed to Iceland and then moved back to Lisbon to take up work
as a chart maker and sailor.;    Granzotto opines that it was a move of
fateful consequence, because Genoa offered little incentive for
world-exploring voyages. Portugal, on the other hand, was by this time a
center for maritime studies, and its explorers were at the forefront of the
epic voyages of discovery.;    After about eight years in Lisbon, plus a
marriage and a number of wide-ranging voyages, the saga now has Columbus
starting his round of visits to the royal courts of Europe, trying to get
monetary backing for a voyage to discover a western route to India.;    Myth
has it that he stood alone in the belief that the world was round, and was
turned down again and again by ignorant nobles unwilling to fight against
traditional geographers.;    In fact, most anybody with an ounce of education
believed by this time that the world was round. What Columbus had to sell was
a new route, one that would be cheaper and more efficient than the overland
routes that had been used for centuries, or the new southern ocean route
around the tip of Africa.;    He first went to the king of Portugal in 1483.
The king, John II, was one of the many Portuguese monarchs who were ardent and
educated supporters of exploration, but he felt the Columbus route was too
uncertain.;    Rejected, Columbus tried next door, in Spain. In 1485, he
arrived at Palos de la Frontera, a tiny port just across the Rio Tinto from
the Portuguese border. Near Palos was the monastery of La Rabida.;    A
devious schemer?;  Those who think Columbus was a devious schemer believe his
arrival in the area was no quirk. At La Rabida were two prelates, Father
Antonio de Marchena and Father Juan Perez.;    De Marchena was a cosmographer,
a man popular at court and a man not ill at ease with the vision of a round
world. And Perez (the plot thickens) was Queen Isabella's personal confessor.;
   By 1486, thanks to the two clergymen, Columbus had been presented at court,
but not to the king and queen. Ferdinand and Isabella were busy kicking the
Moors out of Spain, and the siege of the last major Moorish stronghold,
Granada, was under way. Columbus had to wait until the expulsion was complete
-- a wait that lasted six years.;    In April 1492, the victorious Isabella
met Columbus at the small village of Santa Fe near Granada, one of a series of
meetings the two had over the years. This time, she was ready to support the
scheme.;    But according to Granzotto, Columbus made outrageous demands. In
exchange for royal backing, for example, he wanted 10 percent of all profits
from the new world. He also wanted the title of Admiral of the Open Ocean. The
sovereigns eventually agreed, then later reneged on the deal, starting a
series of lawsuits between the Columbus family and the crown of Spain still
not resolved.;    Isabella did not hock her jewels to pay for the trip, by the
way; her husband, Ferdinand, had to approve all bills, and in this case, the
money came from the royal treasury, and according to historian Morison, from
Columbus himself. The cost to obtain and outfit three ships? Morison says
$14,000.;    Because of crowded conditions in other ports, it was decided that
the voyage would commence from Palos de la Frontera. Isabella, one of
history's darker figures, was a violent anti-Semite who is given credit for
beginning the Spanish Inquisition and for formulating the March 14, 1492,
order for the expulsion of all Jews from Spain.;    ecause of that order, many
southern Spanish ports were filled with refugees; the two sovereigns finally
ordered all ships carrying Jewish exiles to leave port by Aug. 2 -- the day
before Columbus sailed.;    Land Ho!;  It took the three ships -- the immortal
Pinta, Nina and Santa Maria -- more than 40 days to reach the Bahamas
(including a forced layover in the Azores). Ferdinand and Isabella had offered
a lifetime annuity to the first man to spy land in the New World. Granzotto
tells us it was Rodrigo de Triana aboard the Pinta. At 2 a.m., Oct. 12, 1492,
he yelled "Tierra, tierra!" And never got a dime.;    Columbus later claimed
that he was the first to spot land. He said the previous evening, Oct. 11, he
had spotted a candle light on shore. Granzotto, noting that the ships were at
that point about 30 miles offshore, says it would have been impossible to see
the light. "A cruel abuse of power," he calls the action. Columbus kept the
prize.;    Oct. 12 -- Columbus Day in the United States -- he went ashore at
San Salvador Island in the Bahamas and claimed it for Spain. He and his crew
made the first recorded contact between Europeans and the natives of the New
World -- in this case, apparently, the Arawak Indians.;    Columbus took
several Indians back to Spain with him and presented them at the royal court
in Barcelona.;    Columbus made four more voyages to the new lands but
significantly never really recognized that two major land masses were nearby.;
   He explored many of the islands of the Caribbean (and did step ashore in
what is now Venezuela) but found little gold and no proof at all that he had
discovered a new route to India. His health worsened (he caught malaria, had
gout and arthritis), and worse, the coral and sand islands of his new realm
yielded little that increased his fortunes.;    Royal displeasure;  Ferdinand
and Isabella were less than pleased by these voyages. On one, he lost a whole
fleet. On another, he was forced to deal with a mutiny that eventually saw him
returned to Spain in chains.;    The sovereigns had little to show for their
backing and were more and more reluctant to abide by their contract with
Columbus, especially the part that gave him 10 percent of all the goodies
(such as they were) coming back from the Caribbean. Then his chief ally,
Isabella, died in November 1504, less than a month after his return from the
last voyage.;    He and Ferdinand fought a prolonged battle over what was owed
to whom, a battle that apparently worsened Columbus' already frail health (he
was 53 at the time).;    In the spring of 1505, he moved to Valladolid in
northern Spain, where he died a year later. He died too soon to realize that
his dream of gold and glory was real, and that the new world was more than
sandy, barren islands in the middle of the ocean. Within 15 years, Hernan
Cortes had defeated the Aztecs and by 1532, Juan Pizarro had taken control of
the Inca empire.;    Whether he was a gold-hungry, greedy con artist who sold
a bill of goods to a couple of naive monarchs, or a great mariner and
courageous explorer, continues to be a historic debate even today, almost five
centuries later.;    If Columbus/Colombo/Colon were around today, he might be
pleased to know his name is still widely known. Or he might just fly off to
Madrid to see King Juan Carlos and check on that 10 percent he has coming.  </TEXT>
