<CAPTION>  Drawing; DRAWING: On his last trip to the New World in 1502, Christopher
Columbus abandoned two leaking caravels in Jamaica. Marine archaeologists
think they have found the spot, and they hope to dig up the ships.  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  HISTORY; BOAT; FOUND; JAMAICA  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  When he set sail with four small caravels on his final trip to the New World
in 1502, Christopher Columbus expected to find his long-sought shortcut to
Asia and emerge from the disgrace that less than two years before had seen him
stripped of honors and clapped in chains.;    Instead, with two leaking
caravels already abandoned in Panama after a year of perilous wandering, and
the remaining two no longer seaworthy, the ailing 52-year-old admiral and his
mutinous crew barely made it to the beach in this placid bay on the north
coast of Jamaica.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Front  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  COLUMBUS SHIPS REPORTEDLY FOUND
TWO VESSELS BELIEVED TO BE IN JAMAICAN BAY  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     But Columbus' misfortune -- shipwrecked here for a year and five days only
"a crossbow shot," as his son phrased it, from a band of hostile Arawak
Indians -- may be a boon to Jamaica and a team of Texas-based marine
archaeologists. They believe they have found the spot where Columbus ran the
two caravels aground 488 years ago.;    "We are 98 percent sure they are
here," said Dr. James M. Parrent of the Institute of Nautical Archaeology at
Texas A&amp;M University, who, in cooperation with the government of Jamaica,
first began looking for the Columbus caravels in 1982.;    After starting work
in earnest last summer, Parrent said he hopes soon to unearth the keels and
some of the lower hull planking of the caravels "Capitana" and "Santiago de
Palos" -- all that could be expected to remain after almost five centuries
under the bay's bottom -- for expert study and eventual display in a Jamaica
museum.;    "We are charged with locating perhaps the most important historic
archaeological site in the New World," Parrent said, noting that as the
quincentennial of Columbus' first voyage in 1492 approaches, no other trace
has been found of the ships he sailed.;    They not only will be the oldest
European vessels discovered in the Western Hemisphere and the only ones
actually commanded by Columbus, he said, they also will help solve a simple
question that has plagued naval architects and historians for centuries,
namely: What did a caravel look like?;    The Nina and Pinta -- mainstays of
Columbus' first voyage, the Spanish-underwritten expedition that launched him
into Western lore as the finder of America -- were fast-sailing caravels that
he preferred over the larger, more lumbering Santa Maria. Yet no reliable
drawing, painting or naval architect's plan of any of the vessels ever has
been found.;    Although divers have uncovered remains of other 16th-century
vessels thought to be similar to those sailed by Columbus, there remains so
much uncertainty that every attempt to construct replicas, including several
now under way for quincentennial celebrations, has involved guesswork, Parrent
said.  </TEXT>
