<CAPTION>  Photo, diagram; PHOTO: Knight-Ridder; News Service; John Goudie, with a bust
of Columbus, is under investigation for alleged financial improprieties
connected with the presidential commission overseeing the Columbus Day
quincentennial.; DIAGRAM: Mercury News. Columbus' route; Columbus first
crossed the Atlantic in 1111492, reaching an island in the Behamas that he
named San Salvador on Oct. 12. The 500th anniversary trip is far more
ambitious--it probably will included sailing up the continenet by truck and
them sailing in the Pacific Ocean.  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  US; ANNIVERSARY; BOAT; FESTIVAL; SAN-FRANCISCO  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  On Oct. 12, 1992, replicas of Christopher Columbus' ships, the Nina, the Pinta
and the Santa Maria, will sail into San Francisco harbor while millions of
tourists and television viewers look on. Festivities and memorabilia sales
will generate tens of millions of dollars for the tourist industry and win the
city flattering publicity of incalculable worth.;    At least that's what San
Francisco city officials hope for the 500th anniversary of Columbus' voyage.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Front  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  COLUMBUS DAY 1992 JUBILEE IN DIRE STRAITS
AMID SCANDAL, S.F. TRIES TO SAVE ITS ROLE
IN EVENT  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  See also related article on page 8A of this section.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     But now, in what many see as a classic morality tale of greed and
overreaching ambition, the presidential commission in charge of the
celebration is in shambles, its only big sponsor is refusing to shell out any
more money and its former chairman, John Goudie, is under federal
investigation for alleged financial improprieties.;    San Francisco officials
have  been left scrambling to save their mega-buck event, even as they try to
distance themselves from the scandal surrounding deals made under Goudie. They
must, by their own estimate, raise $15 million for the local celebration,
which few people have even heard of.;    "We aren't tainted by them," said
Michael Housh, an assistant to Mayor Art Agnos who handled San Francisco's
1988 bid to the national commission.;    But at the same time individuals and
groups around the country were refusing to do business with Goudie because of
what they allege were unethical requests from him, San Francisco alone among
the cities vying for Columbus Day was willing -- even eager -- to entertain
unusual demands by the chairman to pay the commission cash up front.;    The
world's most; dazzling event ever;    The quincentenary celebration of
Columbus' voyage to America had been promoted -- initially by Spain, later by
other countries including the United States -- as the most dazzling event of
its kind the world had ever seen. Bigger than the Bicentennial. Bigger than
the Statue of Liberty party.;    By one account, Columbus commissions had been
organized in 30 countries, 39 states and 100 cities. Exhibits, movies, tours,
medallions, mugs, T-shirts, sporting events, operas, conferences, books,
scholarships, contests, parties -- the multibillion-dollar Columbus
celebration would have it all.;    And everyone wanted a piece of it.;    The
centerpiece of the pageant was to be the re-creation of the historical voyage
itself: Replicas of the Nina, the Pinta and the Santa Maria would sail from
Spain, host of the 1992 World's Fair and Summer Olympics, and make their way
to the Western Hemisphere, visiting 50 U.S. port cities on an extended tour.; 
  But the prize, which San Francisco won, was who got the show on Columbus Day
1992, the anniversary of the day Columbus landed on an island in the Bahamas
that he named San Salvador.;    City officials, mesmerized by their vision of
hosting the event, have not let a few inconvenient historical facts get in the
way of a lucrative commercial opportunity.;    Columbus never landed anywhere
near San Francisco. The telegenic caravels, supposedly a symbol of 16th
century discovery, will be flying Texaco Inc. flags, and their crew members
will be sporting Texaco emblems. And the ships won't really sail in from
anywhere; they will be carted overland from the East Coast by a subsidiary of
the Ringling Brothers and Barnum &amp; Bailey Circus.;    Commission head;
resigned suddenly;    The person heading this massive jubilee in the United
States was a Republican fund-raiser and Miami-based Cuban-American businessman
who describes himself as a longtime acquaintance of President Bush's son, Jeb,
a Miami developer.;    Goudie, who by all accounts ran the commission like a
private empire, resigned suddenly in December 1990. A spate of news stories
had detailed his personal financial problems, including failing to file
federal tax returns in 1986 and 1987, and allegations of financial
improprieties in the commission's dealings.;    A recent audit by the General
Accounting Office, an investigative arm of the U.S. Congress, found no
commission money unaccounted for, but a separate criminal investigation of
Goudie's activities continues. Goudie denied any wrongdoing in a recent
telephone interview but declined to discuss allegations in detail.;    Several
businessmen and groups say he made demands they considered unethical.;    Bill
Rolen, a Tennessee businessman, wanted to establish a quincentenary center at
the former world's fair site in Knoxville. But Goudie repeatedly made
extraordinary demands, Rolen said, telling the Knoxville group to pay one of
Goudie's friends tens of thousands of dollars for radio advertising in
Venezuela, ordering that a 60-foot yacht on loan to the project be tied up
behind his Coral Gables, Fla., home and finally demanding that two of his
friends be given control of the project.;    "We saw a red flag," said Rolen,
who has worked with world's fair projects extensively. "We were smart enough
not to get involved with him. It was just unethical to do what he was
proposing to do with us. There were too many things that were not proper.";   
Others have similar stories.;    Tony Baltes, a Toledo, Ohio, businessman, and
his partners got cut out of the official quincentenary licensing group, in
which they had invested $500,000, after they started asking about thousands of
dollars in company money that went to a friend of Goudie's.;    Peter Dunev, a
Miami businessman, lost $50,000 in a quincentenary T-shirt project when he,
too, became suspicious about why his checks were being picked up by a close
friend of Goudie's. When Dunev stopped further payments, his contract with the
commission was suspended.;    In each case, these businessmen said, Goudie
ended up screaming abuses over the phone and, in two cases, threatening them
not to make complaints.;    The one big deal Goudie did line up was an
exclusive $5 million contract with Texaco that allowed the oil giant to fly
its logo over the caravels.;    After paying out $1.5 million, Texaco got into
a contract dispute with the commission and has since suspended its donations.;
   San Francisco bid; based on beauty;    Throughout this same period, San
Francisco was eagerly signing up to host the commission's Columbus Day
regatta.;    City officials say San Francisco was selected as the host city
because Mayor Agnos' office put together a bid proposal that highlighted the
city's beauties.;    "We committed to not one cent of funding," said Housh,
Agnos' aide. "We were very smart about that.";    Or maybe San Francisco just
promised more than it had time to deliver.;    Housh made contradictory
statements repeatedly over the past two weeks about the city's negotiations
with Goudie and the commission, and refused to provide documents or provided
only partial documents about the quincentenary.;    But documents obtained
from the commission and interviews with Goudie, commission members, civic
leaders and officials of other cities show that a key reason for San
Francisco's selection was its willingness to pay the commission up front for
the honor.;    The commission set the stage by declaring that it was receiving
only $220,000 annually from Congress and was in desperate need of money. Each
city was asked how it proposed to help.;    San Francisco, in its April 1988
proposal, stated its willingness to reimburse the commission "in very
substantial measure" and said the city "could well make contributions to the
commission's activities beyond reimbursement.";    Goudie, in a telephone
interview from his Coral Gables home, said San Francisco's offer to pay was
"definitely" a factor in its selection. "Plus it's a gorgeous city," Goudie
said, laughing.;    No other city made such a generous, open-ended offer.;   
San Diego ignored that part of the questionnaire. Los Angeles drafted a
carefully worded reply saying it would share any proceeds remaining after all
expenses had been paid and providing that the funds went to "non-revenue
generating activities" mandated by Congress. (San Diego and Los Angeles were
the only two other contenders for the Columbus Day regatta, which was to be
held on the West Coast because of weather restrictions.);    Not long after
San Francisco was chosen in August 1988 as the host site, the city was told to
pay the commission $800,000 before 1992 as part of regatta expenses.;    Still
later, the city was told it would be assessed an additional $2 million in cash
up front, a figure that Goudie had determined, according to commission
members.;    'We would have laughed at them';    Goudie defended his requests
for money, saying the commission was badly under-funded.;    But other groups
and city officials who worked with the national commission said his demands
for cash up front were "outrageous" and "inappropriate.";    "The commission
never asked us for a dime because they knew they'd never get it from us," said
Howard Slotnick, director of Operation Sail in New York, which has handled
numerous regattas and is also in charge of the caravel and tall ship parade
planned there for July 4, 1992. "We would have laughed at them.";    Slotnick
said he advised San Francisco city officials "not to pay any of it" when they
asked for his advice early on in negotiations.;    Cities typically provide
in-kind services -- police and fire services, housing for crews, port
services, accommodations for dignitaries -- but any request for cash up front
is highly unusual, say those who have handled such events.;    Spanish
officials, who have discarded their contract with the presidential commission
and are now organizing the caravel tour themselves, say they believe the money
Goudie asked for had nothing to do with the ships' tour.;    They are not
asking any cities for tour fees, said Miguel Ferrer, director of projects for
the Spain '92 Foundation, a non-profit group operating on behalf of Spain.;   
Both city officials and Goudie say no money ever went from San Francisco to
the commission. The executive director of the commission, however, declined to
make public a list of donations.;    Dispute continues; as time runs out;   
With Columbus Day 1992 only 17 months away, the national commission and Texaco
and Spain remain mired in dispute. The criminal investigation of Goudie's
activities continues. And Spain '92 officials say tour plans are still
tentative, but they intend to honor the designation of San Francisco as host
city for the Columbus Day event.;    Many of those involved in quincentennial
events locally and around the nation say they fear that the Goudie
controversy, coming on top of challenges raised by Indian groups, will keep
big corporate sponsors away.;    California's joint legislative committee on
the quincentennial and its non-profit fund-raising arm have provided five
taxpayer-paid trips to Spain for a few lucky legislators. But the state, which
by April had not raised a cent from corporate sponsors during the committee's
three years of work, will not be much help to San Francisco.;    "The task
ahead will not be easy," said Rep. Thomas Sawyer, D-Ohio, in prepared remarks
at a House subcommittee hearing on the presidential commission late last
month. "The commission's financial position is precarious, its image is
tarnished, and time is running out."  </TEXT>
