<LEADPARA>  WOULD the world have been a different place if an Indian in a sailing ship
landed in Europe before Christopher Columbus hit the Bahamas? You bet.;  
Maybe the Indians would have colonized Spain instead of vice versa. Maybe
Columbus, Ohio, would have a different name. And maybe we'd all be eating
buffalo meat.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Living  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  SAIL THE OCEAN BLUE -- VERY, VERY SLOWLY  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  The New Season; (box) COLUMBUS AND THE AGE OF DISCOVERY; Sunday-Wednesday
nights at 9, Ch. 9;; Monday and following three Monday nights at 9, Ch. 54.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     But even those who would rewrite history can't change it, and it was
Columbus who came west instead of the Indians going east. And that voyage did
set off a chain-reaction of epic events, both good and evil, which affect the
entire globe to this day.;   With the 500th anniversary of Columbus' first
voyage just a year away, the debate over its meaning is about to become a
cottage industry.;   And no cottage industry is complete without a TV show: in
this case PBS's seven-hour "Columbus and the Age of Discovery," public TV's
attempt to do for the discovery of America what it did last year for the Civil
War.;   But alas, Zvi Dor-Ner, the film maker who spent 10 years putting
"Columbus" together, is no Ken Burns, the man behind the magnificent "Civil
War." In Burns' hands these seven hours wouldn't seem so much like 12 or 14.; 
 What "Columbus" offers are two or three interesting hours about "history's
most stunning accident" -- stretched to seven mostly dull ones. Beautiful, but
dull.;   By the time the series really hits its stride in hour six, I'm afraid
no one will be watching.;   Most people will have a hard time staying with
Sunday's opening two hours, which meander around the globe, setting up
Columbus' times, his motivation and his struggle to get someone to finance his
dream of sailing west to reach the East. Surely this could have been done in
one hour instead of two.;   Even the prologue is prolonged, as narrator Will
Lyman ("Vietnam: A Television History") asks, "Should we celebrate Columbus'
great achievement, or should we mourn a world forever lost?";   The answer, of
course, is both. No matter what horrors followed -- and the decimation of the
native population of Hispaniola from half a million to 500 in little more than
25 years, six of them while Columbus himself was governor, certainly is a
horror -- the voyage itself was an astounding achievement of navigation and
courage. We see that chronicled in Part 3, "The Crossing.";   It's what
Columbus and others did after they landed that's so debatable, substituting
one culture for another and rarely gently.;   The debate is dealt with in
"Columbus" -- and not just by experts but by real people in the lands
affected. Like everything else here, though, the show takes a long time to get
there.;   If you hang in, however, you will learn something: that Martin
Pinzon is seen as the real hero of the first voyage by many Spaniards; or how
the exchange of crops and animals between the New and Old Worlds put horses on
the American plains, brought potatoes to Ireland, corn to Europe and sugar
cane to the Caribbean, for example.;   With cane, sadly, came slaves, a far
less noble part of the trade, explored in the series' most successful hour,
the sixth one, called "The Columbian Exchange.";   The conclusion, "In Search
of Columbus," lays out the astounding paradox of the man: "Christopher
Columbus, an Italian seaman sailing for the Catholic monarchies of Spain, has
been embraced as a national hero by the mainly English-speaking, Protestant
United States of America in a land he never set foot in, that he refused to
believe existed and that was named for someone else.";   Had the rest of this
series been as succinct, it would have been a glorious triumph instead of such
a tedious trip.  </TEXT>
