<SECTION>  Travel  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  GOODBYE, COLUMBUS
EVEN HIS BURIAL SPOT IS A SUBJECT OF MUCH
DISPUTE  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Cover Story
The Great Columbus Chase
Last in a four-part series  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     The Cafe El Norte, facing the Plaza Mayor in the heart of this fairly plain
city on the plains of northern Andalusia. The Cafe El Norte, busy bar and
social center. The Cafe El Norte, last resting place for the Admiral of the
Open Ocean, Don Cristobal Colon, the dude who discovered America.;    Or is
it?;    Historians are in general agreement about the final fate of
Christopher Columbus. He made four voyages to the New World, starting in 1492
-- voyages that eventually destroyed his health and soured his soul. His last
years were spent haggling with the king of Spain about the profits he had
coming from the discovery of the Western Hemisphere.;    When he was given
backing by Ferdinand and Isabella in 1492, he extracted an agreement that
included some major concessions by the crown, including a 10 percent share of
all profits from the new lands, as well as honorary titles.;    The crown
chose to redefine the agreement toward the end of Columbus' life, taking away
most of his claims. (Despite this, he was quite rich.) He was allowed to keep
his titles -- as were his heirs. Today, there is a Cristobal Colon in Spain, a
young man who still has the right to be called the Admiral of the Open Sea,
the title  Columbus insisted he be given before he took off for the edge of
the world.;    Columbus moved to Valladolid in 1506 and died there May 20.
That much is sure. What happened after that is the subject of some debate
among scholars.;    One version has him being buried in Valladolid, then being
moved to a monastery in Seville sometime between 1509 and 1514. In 1537, he
was moved to Santo Domingo (the Bahamian island where he supposedly landed in
1492). In 1795, his remains were moved to Havana, where they stayed until the
end of the Spanish-American War. They were then sent back to Seville and
buried in the great cathedral there.;     Italian biographer Gianni Granzotto
has the most intriguing the story -- and this is where the Cafe El Norte comes
on the scene.;    Granzotto says that on the Plaza Mayor -- right where the
Cafe El Norte sits today -- there was a Franciscan monastery at the time of
Columbus' death. The monastery, St. Francis, contained a burial crypt.;    The
crypt now lies beneath the floor of the Cafe El Norte and Granzotto says it
contains the bones of Christopher Columbus, devout Franciscan.;    So it was
no surprise that after the usual tourist inquiry was made -- i.e., where's the
body? -- the owner of the Cafe El Norte himself arrived at the table and
allowed there was a chance Don Cristobal Colon was moldering beneath his
feet.;    "Many Americans, many English, they come in here and ask to see his
grave. We do not know that it really is there because that was long ago. But
perhaps, why not? It is an interesting little story, is it not?";    And so
you won't be totally disappointed that no tours of the Columbus bones are
available (or at least offered), he hands out free Cafe El Norte calendars as
souvenirs and walks away to discuss the bullfight.;    So, who cares?; 
Goodbye, Columbus, write if you find work -- or the New World, whatever -- and
don't call us, we'll call you. Valladolid, unlike most of the other European
haunts of the great explorer, seems mostly indifferent to its connection with
Spanish history.;    Yeah, there's a statue of Columbus, but this is no big
deal -- in Andalusia and most other parts of Spain, any town with more than 10
people is likely to have at least one bronze rendering of our Italian hero.;  
 The house in Valladolid where he died apparently is gone, but there is a
small museum nearby that once was owned by the Columbus family and serves as a
symbolic tie to the past. (In some tourism literature, the museum is, in fact,
described as the house where he died.);    But nowhere in the city are there
signs directing the curious to the museum, and it's clear from the patrons of
the Cafe El Norte that the exact spot where the Great Explorer dropped his
last anchor is of little importance -- especially on the afternoon of the
Madrid bullfights.;    The museum is closed this year in anticipation of the
500th anniversary of his first voyage next year, and there are some historical
displays going up around the Plaza Mayor.;    In official city maps, which
have illustrated notes about many historical buildings around the city, there
is some mention of the statue honoring "the illustrious Almirante del Mar
Oceano -- Admiral of the Open Ocean," but the location of the museum and house
are given only a single line -- and many locals, when asked, seem not to know
where the house is.;    Seville's claim;  Most of the Columbus madness around
the vast province of Andalusia is centered in Seville, site of the 1992
world's fair. The folks in Seville have no doubt about the bones -- they are
now, always have been, always will be stashed in the cathedral of Seville.
Valladolid? The Cafe El Norte? Nothing but the ramblings of an uninformed
historian -- an Italian one at that.;    Columbus used Seville as a base for
several of his later trips to the New World, and it also was from here that
the other Italian explorer -- Amerigo Vespucci, the one with the good press
agent -- sailed. (Two continents were named after Vespucci; Columbus got one
American country, one Canadian province and a nice town in Ohio.);    The 1992
Seville Expo is one of two big deals going on in Spain next year, the other
being the summer Olympic Games in Barcelona. And, like Barcelona, big chunks
of Seville are torn up in preparation.;    The Expo, like the Olympics, is
tied into the 500th anniversary of the first Columbus voyage in 1492. The Expo
theme is "The Age of Discovery," and the Columbus-Seville connection is being
pushed hard.;    Dem bones, dem bones;  Millions of people are expected to
wander through Seville next summer to check out the fair and soak up some
Columbiana. But the guest of honor won't be around. Seville can make all the
rash claims it wants, and hold all the parties it can, and hire herds of
public relations types to hype the 500th anniversary of the great admiral's
exploits. But everyone knows old Chris is stuck in Valladolid, under the floor
of the Cafe El Norte.;    We'll leave him there, 500 years and half a
continent away from where he started back in Genoa. One thing about Columbus
-- you might not admire him much, but you have to admit he got around. And
following in his footsteps around Europe won't make you any better historian,
but it surely will lead you to some great food, nice folks and pretty
scenery.;    It almost makes you want to hop on a leaky old boat and sail off
to the edge of the world.;    Almost.  </TEXT>
