<HEAD>Pilgrims Sailed in the Pinto? Wait a Minute ...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELLEVUE, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   How's this for revisionist history? The
pilgrims sailed to America in the Pinto. Paul Revere wrote ``The
Star-Spangled Banner.'' Sandra Day O'Connor is chief justice of the
U.S. Supreme Court.
   And Gen. Douglas MacArthur said, ``Give me liberty or give me
death.'' Or was it Martin Luther King Jr.?
   These are samplings of responses from community-college students
to questions that might be asked of immigrants seeking U.S.
citizenship.
   Just five of 119 students at Bellevue Community College managed
a passing grade of 70 percent or better.
   ``This is pretty bad,'' said Aslam Khan, head of the college's
political science department, who administered the test.
   ``Why should we give these questions to foreigners when our own
citizens don't know what is going on?'' asked the Pakistan-born
Khan, who took such a test when he became a naturalized citizen.
   Less than half the students knew that the supreme law of the
land is the Constitution.
   When asked what kind of government the United States has, many
answered ``capitalist,'' rather than a democracy.
   Some said the pilgrims left Europe because they were searching
for something to colonize, apparently forgetting the religious
persecution that prompted them to flee to the New World.
   A decade ago, Khan gave a similar test of 10 questions to 118
students. Six passed.
   ``It's not getting any better,'' he said.
   It may be good for a few snickers when a student identifies
Abraham Lincoln as the principal author of the Declaration of
Independence, but when only one student answers 29 of the 30
questions correctly and just 18 get 60 percent right, everybody
should be concerned, Khan said.
   ``I think people should know what is going on in this country,''
he said. ``We really do need a course in remedial American
Government.''
   For the record:
   _ The Pinta, not the Pinto, was one of three ships used by
Christopher Columbus, along with the Nina and the Santa Maria. The
pilgrims sailed in the Mayflower.
   _ Francis Scott Key wrote the national anthem, while Paul Revere
warned American revolutionaries the British were coming.
   _ Ms. O'Connor is the first woman to serve on the Supreme Court,
which has yet to have a woman chief justice.
   _ Patrick Henry preferred death over tyranny in his famous to
the Virginia House of Burgesses, while MacArthur is remembered for
pledging ``I shall return'' to the Philippines and civil-rights
leader King for his ``I have a dream'' speech.
</TEXT>
