<CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: 'Crown of Columbus' is the first novel Erdrich and Dorris wrote
together  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  BOOK; REVIEW  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  THE CROWN OF COLUMBUS; By Michael Dorris and Louise Erdrich  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Arts &amp; Books  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  COLUMBIAN COLLABORATION
LOUISE ERDRICH, MICHAEL DORRIS CREATE A WONDERFUL
TREASURE HUNT  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Books
Giles, a regular reviewer for the Mercury News, teaches writing at San
Francisco State University. She is this year's winner of the reviewing
citation from the National Book Critics Circle.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>  HarperCollins, 384 pp., $21.95;  THERE has already been a lot of hype about
"The Crown of Columbus," and there is probably going to be a lot more. The
novel sold for an enormous amount of money (the advance alone was an
unprecedented three-quarters of a million dollars). The Book-of-the-Month Club
has bid on it, so have the magazines and translators; Michelle Pfeiffer owns
the movie rights.;    The authors, Michael Dorris and Louise Erdrich, are
already on a national publicity tour. Handsome and appealing, they make fine
spokespeople for their own work and provide unusually interesting copy for
articles and interviews. Both are of mixed American Indian descent, and both
grew up, at least partly, on reservations. They have been married 10 years and
are raising six children together. Prize-winning authors on their own
(Erdrich's "Love Medicine" won the National Book Critics Circle Award for
Fiction in 1984, and Dorris' "The Broken Cord" won the National Book Critics
Circle Award for Non-Fiction in 1989), the two are used to reading and
commenting on each other's work, but they have never openly collaborated on a
full-length book before.;    And the book? Well, it's great. "The Crown of
Columbus" feels exactly like the family-written book it is. Unpretentious and
engaging, it has more charm and humor than readers may have found in earlier
Dorris and/or Erdrich works, without sacrificing any of the intelligence or
feeling. The very first sentence ("In the warm pink-gold of a Caribbean
afternoon, something marvelous washed up from the sea") sets the tone, and
this light and literate quality lasts throughout the book.;    The plot
focuses on the on-again, off-again romance between two very different
Dartmouth professors as they try to second-guess Christopher Columbus -- who
he was, what he wanted, what his legacy to America really consisted of.;   
Vivian Twostar, who narrates part of the book, is a spunky, outspoken
40-year-old single mother who teaches American Indian studies in the
anthropology department. Forced by the requirements of her tenure year to
write an article on Columbus, whom she refers to sarcastically as "Mr.
Navigator," Vivian begins her research with reluctance. She wants what every
"other sensible person of full or partial American Indian descent" wants --
that is, she wants to nail him.;    Vivian has a clear idea of what life was
like for her people before Columbus landed. The Indians on the tiny island of
Guanahani, in the Bahamas, were, she tells us, "a healthy pleasure-loving
group, laid-back beach bums and surfers, with absolutely no aptitude for
destruction." They lived in "an endless summer of surf and starry nights"
until, in 1492, the fateful sails of the Nina, the Pinta and the Santa Maria
appeared on the horizon. Then, Vivian fumes, they all ran down to meet the
ships -- they had, after all, no reason to think the Spaniards weren't simply
bringing "more good news.";    Roger Williams, an elegant, emotionally inept
academician who talks to students and fellow professors using the "odd,
two-fingered hand position Christ used in Bible story illustrations," is
writing about Columbus for different reasons: He is interested in the man as
an Italian who sailed for Spain, a Jew who converted to Christianity, a
navigator who never found the "Orient" he aimed for. Roger, a narrative poet,
is writing an unrhymed monologue titled "Diary of a Lost Man" that starts with
Columbus' admission: "I do not know myself.";    The two, Roger and Vivian,
have a comic confrontation in the Dartmouth library when Roger's cough alerts
Vivian's anger. "The first European who stood on the North American continent
and coughed," Vivian remembers, "probably indirectly killed more Indians than
. . . Custer ever imagined in his favorite wet dream." They fall in love, but
break apart when Vivian learns she is pregnant. They stay apart until Roger
learns to develop "a tolerance for change" that includes accepting Vivian, her
teen-age son Nash ("just spell it G-N-A-S-H"), her irritable Navajo
grandmother and their new baby, Violet -- the "whole unruly entourage.";    In
the meantime, both continue to track down information on Columbus. They agree
on one fact: Columbus was a slave trader. The gold he failed to find in the
New World he supplanted with natives he bragged would make "good and
intelligent servants" for Spain.;    But what are these references to a
mysterious "crown" in the journals and notes? When a sinister millionaire
named Cobb offers to help put the pieces together, Vivian, Roger, Nash and the
baby fly to his mansion in the Bahamas. Roger sees nothing but fleas and
mosquitoes on the tropical island, and Vivian's view is also bleak: The "poor
soil, bright colors, dark people, junked automobiles" all remind her of a
reservation. Cobb's private beach is, however, the promised paradise. And as
Cobb's clues tally with Vivian's, the race to find the "real" Columbus speeds
up.;     "The Crown of Columbus" is an old-fashioned treasure-hunt story that
offers a little bit for everyone -- there are bats, sharks, caves,
kidnappings, codes and karate chops, as well as poems by Donne and Roger
Williams, entries from Columbus' diary, Navajo chants and wonderful
descriptions of university librarians, childbirth and stoned 16-year-old boys.
The only thing missing is the recipe for Vivian's chili.;     There are, to be
sure, some flat parts and some thin characters. Columbus himself remains sadly
elusive. There is a Nancy Drew-gets-together-with-the-Hardy-Boys quality that
may put off the sophisticated. But the good spirit of the book is contagious,
and that, essentially, is what makes it so effective.;    "The Crown of
Columbus" feels as if it was written in fun, conceived and constructed in an
atmosphere of camaraderie, respect and good faith. If only Columbus had landed
on our shores with half these qualities . . .  </TEXT>
