<LEADPARA>  Three Viking ships sailed up the Potomac River on Wednesday, commemorating
Leif Ericson's landing in the New World about 1,000 years ago and challenging
the 500th anniversary hoopla celebrating that Christopher-come-lately.;   The
78-foot flagship Gaia, a replica of the wooden, single-masted Viking longboat,
docked at a Georgetown wharf shortly before noon on Leif Ericson Day after a
5,300-mile voyage across the North Atlantic that began May 17 in Bergen,
Norway.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Front  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  LEIF ERICSON LANDING CELEBRATED
ICELAND'S LEADER, NORWAY'S QUEEN IN U.S. TO BOOST
VIKING EXPLORER  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     The Gaia and two Viking escort vessels that joined the voyage at Nova
Scotia were greeted by noisy blasts from ancient Norse birch-bark horns and
cheers from a dockside crowd that included President Vigdis Finnbogadottir of
Iceland and Queen Sonja of Norway.;   Also welcoming the Norse sailors was
former Vice President Walter Mondale, a Minnesotan of Norwegian stock. Playing
it safe, he praised the epic voyages of both Ericson and Christopher Columbus
as "victories of the human spirit.";   Speaking to a reporter, Mondale
recalled being spanked as a child for bragging, but on this occasion he
couldn't resist.;   "We got here 500 years early," he said, beaming. "We
didn't need any money. We just did it.";   No one knows exactly when or where
Ericson landed in the New World. Many scholars believe the Vikings reached the
northern coast of Newfoundland about 1,000 years ago and settled there for a
year before returning home.;   Ericson called the place "Vinland."
Archaeologists have found the remains of an early Viking settlement at
L'Anse-aux-Meadows on the northern tip of Newfoundland but none of the grape
vines that Ericson is said to have found there.;   After the speechmaking and
a celebratory lunch, the Icelandic president and the Norwegian queen paid a
courtesy call on President Bush at the White House, thus deftly upstaging
Cristobal Colon, a 20th-generation direct descendant of Columbus.;   Colon, a
42-year-old Spanish naval officer, wasn't scheduled to meet Bush until today.
He is touring the United States to help celebrate Columbus Day and launch
yearlong festivities celebrating the 500th anniversary of his ancestor's
landing in the New World.;   The Smithsonian Institution is sponsoring a
variety of Columbus anniversary events, and the National Gallery of Art on
Saturday will open its blockbuster "Circa 1492" exhibition of artworks from
the Columbus era. King Juan Carlos I and Queen Sofia of Spain got a sneak
preview of the exhibit Tuesday.  </TEXT>
