<HL> International: Spain to Celebrate Columbus's Voyage At an $800 Million Coming-Out Party </HL>
<AUTHOR> Nicholas Bray (WSJ Staff) </AUTHOR>
<SO> </SO>
<CO> EUROP </CO>
<DATELINE> SEVILLE, Spain  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Spain has begun restoring the Seville monastery where Christopher Columbus rested between sailings, and where he lay buried for a quarter century after he died, as part of an $800 million extravaganza to commemorate his discovery of America. 

   But Expo '92, as the project is called, will be more than just a celebration of the 500th anniversary of Columbus's voyage to the New World. 
It will also be an international coming-out party for Spain's emergence as a modern democracy. 

   Falling nearly two decades after the death in 1975 of right-wing dictator Gen. Francisco Franco, 1992 is the final year before Spain's full integration into the European Community and also the year of the Barcelona Olympics. 
In addition, 1992 is the year the EC is supposed to dismantle all remaining trade barriers within its borders -- a major test for Spanish industry, which is modernizing but still shackled by a history of state paternalism and protectionism. 

   "It can reinforce the idea Spain is regaining a position within the Western community, that it isn't a Third World country but one that also has some cards to play," says Juan Diez Nicolas, a sociologist. 

   The exposition in Seville will run from April until Oct. 12 -- 500 years to the day from Columbus's landing on the Caribbean island of San Salvador. 
It is expected to attract 20 million visitors. 

   The budget of more than $800 million is to be covered by entry charges, the sale of television and souvenir rights, and sponsorship by commercial firms. 
Like the 1984 Los Angeles Olympics, Expo '92 is supposed to pay for itself. 

   There are doubters: Seville, a city of 700,000, is better known for flamenco dancing and music and bullfights than for science and high technology -- the themes of the exposition. 
How much public interest it will generate isn't evident, even to some Spaniards. 
"I really don't know whether the exhibition has a clear enough theme to arouse much enthusiasm," comments a Madrid businessman. 

   The former Carthusian monastery where Columbus often stayed and where he was buried from 1509 until his body was moved to Santo Domingo in 1536, will be the centerpiece of Expo '92. 
Converted into a ceramics factory in the early 19th century and vacant since 1982, it is being rebuilt as an architectural showcase. 
King Juan Carlos, hailed in Spain as a national savior for thwarting an attempted military coup in 1981, will spend much of his time there welcoming foreign leaders. 

   More than 70 nations, including all of Latin America, the U.S., the Soviet Union, China, Japan and most European nations, have already said they will take part in Expo '92. 
Manuel Olivencia, a law professor who is the exposition's government-appointed director, wants to beat the record set in Osaka, when 77 nations took part. 

   In the buildup to 1992, about 500 billion pesetas ($4.2 billion) is being spent on such major public-works projects as a high-speed train link with Madrid, highways and improved airport facilities. 
Some 200,000 jobs are expected to be created, and in Seville real-estate prices have more than quintupled in the formerly depressed area along the Guadalquivir River overlooking the exhibition site. 

   Four Spanish banks have agreed to provide $67 million for rights to the Expo '92 logo and mascot. 
Multinational companies like Fujitsu Ltd. of Japan, Alcatel N.V. of France, Siemens AG of West Germany, N.V. Philips of the Netherlands and Xerox Corp. of the U.S. are paying $8.2 million to act as official sponsors. 

   In hopes of avoiding a debacle, planners have studied other world expositions, including the money-losing 1967 Montreal Expo, and some smaller international expositions such as those in Tsukuba, Japan in 1985 and in Vancouver in 1986. 

   Expo director Olivencia acknowledges the challenge he faces. 
Success or failure in Seville, he says, is likely to be crucial for similar projects planned by other nations between 1992 and 2001. 

   Vienna and Budapest have proposed a joint international exposition in 1995 to commemorate, among other things, the 50th anniversary of the end of World War II and the 40th anniversary of Austria's restored independence. 
In Hong Kong, businessmen have proposed an exposition in 1997, the year Britain is to hand back the colony to China. 
Hanover, West Germany, is bidding to hold a world's fair in 1998 or 2000, and there are rumors of other bids from Miami, Venice and Oslo. 

   After a period when many people thought the era of such extravaganzas was over, "there has been a resurgence of interest," says Marie-Helene Defrene, secretary-general of the International Expositions Bureau, an inter-governmental agency based in Paris. 

</TEXT>
