<HEAD>Commission Faces Probe, Search for New Chairman</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Monday correct in 2nd graf</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A financially troubled presidential commission
planning the 500th anniversary celebration of Columbus' 1492 voyage
to America faces a congressional investigation and a search for a
new chairman.
   John Goudie of Miami resigned Monday as head of the Christopher
Columbus Quincentenary Jubilee Commission out of what his deputy
said was a sense of frustration.
   Goudie was a fund-raiser for the unsuccessful re-election effort
of Florida Gov. Bob Martinez, who is President Bush's nominee as
director of national drug control policy. He was appointed to the
commission by former President Reagan.
   The commission is $600,000 in arrears on an agreement to pay
Spain for replicas of Columbus' three ships. The ships are to tour
American ports for the celebration.
   Texaco Inc., which has pledged $5 million, stopped its donations
in September because of ``some technical matters and overall
management of the program,'' Texaco spokesman K. Peter Maneri said
Tuesday. He said the company hopes the problems, which he refused
to detail, can be worked out and financial support resumed.
   Another potential sponsor, Chrysler Corp., says it wants to
clear up unspecified contractual questions before making a donation
of more than $1 million.
   A House Post Office and Civil Service subcommittee, meanwhile,
is delving into Goudie's longtime friendship with Manuel Gonzalez,
a Miami businessmen who has been involved in plans for the
celebration.
   A businessman, Peter Dunev of Miami, paid $50,000 for the right
to place the 500th anniversary logo on T-shirts. Gonzalez came by
Dunev's office last summer to pick up the checks for the $50,000,
Dunev said in an interview.
   The checks were made out to Christopher Columbus Licensing Group
Inc. of Miami and New York. The commission has awarded the
licensing group a contract enabling it to keep 85 percent of
commission-related sales on T-shirts and souvenirs.
   Bill Rolen, a Knoxville, Tenn., businessman who had made a
proposal for the celebration, said Goudie introduced him to
Gonzalez as a friend who might be able to provide Rolen with
financing
   Rolen said the two didn't do business because Gonzalez wanted
part ownership in Rolen's proposed venture. It was to have been a
renovation of a former world's fair exposition hall in Knoxville
for the Columbus celebration.
   Gonzalez did not return telephone calls to his home and office
in Miami. Goudie also couldn't be reached.
   However, the commission's deputy director, Jana Joustra, said
Goudie's resignation from the non-salaried, part-time post was
``completely voluntary.'' She said Goudie ``got fed up'' with the
problems, the lack of financial support and the criticism he faced
after spending a great deal of his own time on the project.
   ``Nobody appreciated it,'' she said.
   Congress appropriates $212,000 a year for the commission to pay
part of the salaries and rent for the six-member staff.
   The congressional subcommittee's investigation of the commission
will continue, said the panel's chairman, Rep. Thomas Sawyer,
D-Ohio.
</TEXT>
