<LEADPARA>  Canadian Indians set off in a protest ship Wednesday to intercept a flotilla
re-enacting Columbus' first voyage from Spain to the Americas. The Indians
said they were not seeking a confrontation with the flotilla, which includes
replicas of the three caravels Columbus sailed, but would try to block its
advance if the flotilla did not stop.;   "What we want is a peaceful and
friendly dialogue," Wii Seeks, a Gitksan tribal chief who leads the protest
mission, told reporters. He said they sought an apology from Spain, which is
sponsoring the commemorative voyage, and other nations for celebrating
Columbus' arrival in the New World. The Indians are aboard the Sea Shepherd 2,
owned and operated by a California-based environmental group, the Sea Shepherd
Conservation Society.  </LEADPARA>
