<HEAD>Report: Columbus Commission Under Financial Scrutiny</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the presidential commission
organizing the 500th anniversary celebration of Columbus' voyage to
America says he has submitted his resignation amid questions about
his and the panel's finances.
   John Goudie, a Miami Republican and real estate businessman, was
quoted as saying in The New York Times today that he sent a letter
to President Bush announcing his resignation from the unsalaried
post.
   Goudie, who was appointed by President Reagan in 1985, denied
any wrongdoing.
   ``It's time for me to bow out,'' he said, adding that the
commision needed ``some favorable publicity.''
   There was no immediate word on whether Goudie's resignation was
accepted. White House spokesman Sean Walsh had no comment on the
report.
   A House subcommittee has been looking at whether the Christopher
Columbus Quincentenary Jubilee Commission has awarded contracts
properly. Some of the arrangements under scrutiny involve friends
of Goudie's, the Times said.
   The congressional panel plans to hold hearings next year into
the running of the commission after an audit by the General
Accounting Office, the newspaper said.
   The 5-year-old commission is $600,000 behind on an agreement
with Spain, which has built replicas of the three ships Columbus
led to the New World, because Texaco Inc., a main sponsor, has
stopped its donations, the newspaper said.
   Texaco and Goudie said the money was halted because of a
contractual dispute.
   Goudie said he is resigning because publicity over the Texaco
incident has jeopardized a pledge from the Chrysler Corp.
   One member of the commission, Virgil Dechant of Hamden, Conn.,
said he knew nothing of a resignation by Goudie. Dechant said that
to his knowledge, the commission had no particular financial
problems.
   Another member of the commission, Mary Jane Checci of
Washington, also said she knew nothing of a resignation.
</TEXT>
